<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
      Sery Link entitlements — macOS Hardened Runtime opt-outs.

      Why disable library validation?
      DuckDB downloads + dlopens its own extensions at runtime
      (httpfs, parquet, etc.) into ~/.duckdb/extensions/. Those
      extensions are signed by DuckDB Labs, not by us. Hardened
      Runtime's default library validation refuses to load any dylib
      whose Team ID differs from the host process — so the app
      crashes with:

        "code signature in '...httpfs.duckdb_extension' not valid for
         use in process: mapping process and mapped file (non-platform)
         have different Team IDs"

      Disabling library validation lets DuckDB's signed-but-not-by-us
      extensions load. The dylibs are still signed (just by a
      different identity); they just can't be unsigned ad-hoc.

      Why allow-unsigned-executable-memory?
      Some DuckDB extensions JIT-compile query plans to native code
      and need to allocate executable memory. Hardened Runtime would
      otherwise SIGKILL the process on the first JIT.

      Why allow-dyld-environment-variables?
      pdfium / pandoc resources resolve relative paths via
      DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH / DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH set by Tauri's
      bundling. Hardened Runtime ignores those by default.

      Network entitlements: the app talks to api.sery.ai + cloud
      storage endpoints, so network.client is required.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables</key>
    <true/>

    <!-- Network access — required for cloud-storage sources, the
         WebSocket tunnel back to api.sery.ai, and the auto-updater. -->
    <key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
    <true/>

    <!-- File access — Sery Link is a "browse the user's files"
         desktop app, so user-selected and downloads/pictures/movies
         entitlements are part of the core capability. -->
    <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-only</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
